A middleware program is a software component that sits between the web server and the application, intercepting and processing requests before they reach the application. Here is an example of a simple middleware program written in Python using the Flask web framework to filter all incoming requests on a website:

```python
from flask import Flask, request, abort

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.before_request
def filter_requests():
    # Add your filtering logic here
    if not request.headers.get('API-KEY') == 'SECRET_KEY':
        abort(401)

# Define your routes here
@app.route('/')
def home():
    return 'Welcome to the website!'

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run()
```

In this example, the `filter_requests` function is decorated with the `before_request` decorator, which means that it will be executed before any request is processed. In this function, we are checking if the request contains an `API-KEY` header with a value of `SECRET_KEY`. If the header is not present or the value is incorrect, the request is aborted with an HTTP 401 Unauthorized error.

You can modify and extend `filter_requests` function to add your own custom filtering logic. For instance, you can check the request IP against a blacklist, check the request method, validate the request payload or headers, and so on.

Once the middleware has processed the request, it is passed on to the appropriate route handler, where the application can process it and generate a response.

Here's an example that uses HTML5 canvas and JavaScript to create an animated ball that moves from left to right and back across the middle of the screen:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Animated Ball</title>
	<style>
		body {
			margin: 0;
			padding: 0;
			overflow: hidden;
		}
		canvas {
			display: block;
		}
	</style>
</head>
<body>
	<canvas id="canvas"></canvas>

	<script>
		// get the canvas element from the DOM
		var canvas = document.getElementById("canvas");

		// set the canvas dimensions and position
		canvas.width = window.innerWidth;
		canvas.height = window.innerHeight;
		canvas.style.position = "absolute";

		// get the canvas context for drawing
		var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");

		// initialize the ball position and velocity
		var x = 0;
		var y = canvas.height / 2;
		var vx = 5;

		// define the animation loop
		function animate() {
			// clear the canvas
			ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

			// draw the ball
			ctx.beginPath();
			ctx.arc(x, y, 20, 0, Math.PI*2, false);
			ctx.fillStyle = "red";
			ctx.fill();

			// update the ball position
			x += vx;

			// if the ball reaches the canvas edge, reverse direction
			if (x < 0 || x > canvas.width) {
				vx = -vx;
			}

			// request the next animation frame
			requestAnimationFrame(animate);
		}

		// start the animation loop
		animate();
	</script>
</body>
</html>
```

The code above creates a canvas element, sets its dimensions to cover the entire screen, and gets the canvas context for drawing. Then it sets the initial position and velocity of the ball and defines an animation loop that clears the canvas, draws the ball, updates its position, and reverses its direction when it reaches the canvas edge. Finally, it starts the animation loop using the requestAnimationFrame method.

Here's the C++ program to print Pascal's Triangle up to N rows:

```
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  int n;
  cout << "Enter the number of rows: ";
  cin >> n;

  int arr[n][n];
  // initialize first two rows
  arr[0][0] = 1;
  arr[1][0] = 1;
  arr[1][1] = 1;

  for(int i=2; i<n; i++) {
    arr[i][0] = 1; // set first element to 1
    for(int j=1; j<=i; j++) {
        // calculate each element using the formula
        arr[i][j] = arr[i-1][j-1] + arr[i-1][j];
    }
  }

  // print the triangle
  for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
    for(int j=0; j<=i; j++) {
        cout << arr[i][j] << " ";
    }
    cout << endl;
  }

  return 0;
}
```

The output will be in the form of Pascal's Triangle up to the desired number of rows.

Here is a Java program that can be used to print all permutations of an array:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Permutations {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] array = {1, 2, 3};
        permutate(array, array.length);

    }
    private static void permutate(int[] array, int n) {
        if (n == 1) {
            System.out.println(Arrays.toString(array));
            return;
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            swap(array, i, n - 1);
            permutate(array, n - 1);
            swap(array, i, n - 1);
        }

    }
    private static void swap(int[] array, int i, int j) {
        int temp = array[i];
        array[i] = array[j];
        array[j] = temp;
    }
}
```

This program uses recursion to print all permutations of a given array. The main method calls the permutate method, which takes the array and its length as arguments. The permutate method swaps elements of the array and recursively calls itself until all permutations have been printed. Then the swap method is used to swap the elements back to their original positions.

Here is a JavaScript program to remove all duplicated elements from an array: 

```javascript
function removeDuplicates(array){
    let uniqueArray = [...new Set(array)];
    return uniqueArray;
}
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 3];
let result = removeDuplicates(arr);
console.log(result);
```

### Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]

Explanation: 
In the above program, we have defined the function named `removeDuplicates` which takes an array as an argument. Within this function, we created a new Set and passed our array in the set. Passing the array in the Set remove all the duplicate values from it. We then convert this unique set back to an array using the `...`(spread operator). So, we got our new uniqueArray with no duplicates.
